31 pursuant to ORS 286A.560 to 286A.585 in an amount that produces $5,000,000 in net proceeds
32 for the purposes described in subsection (2) of this section, plus an additional amount esti-
33 mated by the State Treasurer to be necessary to pay bond-related costs.
34 (2) Net proceeds of lottery bonds issued under this section must be transferred to the
35 department for deposit in the OBDD Economic Development Distributions Fund established
36 under section 28, chapter 748, Oregon Laws 2017, for distribution to the City of Silverton for
37 a new wastewater treatment plant.
38 (3) The Legislative Assembly finds that the use of lottery bond proceeds will create jobs,
39 further economic development, finance public education or restore and protect parks,
40 beaches, watersheds and native fish and wildlife, and is authorized based on the finding that
41 wastewater treatment plants are an integral part of the commercial and industrial
42 infrastructure of this state, and improving wastewater treatment will promote economic
43 development and watershed health.
44 SECTION 37. (1) For the biennium ending June 30, 2027, at the request of the Oregon
45 Department of Administrative Services, after the department consults with the Oregon
[23]

A-Eng. SB 5701
1 Business Development Department, the State Treasurer is authorized to issue lottery bonds
2 pursuant to ORS 286A.560 to 286A.585 in an amount that produces $2,000,000 in net proceeds
3 for the purposes described in subsection (2) of this section, plus an additional amount esti-
4 mated by the State Treasurer to be necessary to pay bond-related costs.
5 (2) Net proceeds of lottery bonds issued under this section must be transferred to the
6 department for deposit in the OBDD Economic Development Distributions Fund established
7 under section 28, chapter 748, Oregon Laws 2017, for distribution to the City of Grants Pass
8 for wastewater infrastructure improvements.
9 (3) The Legislative Assembly finds that the use of lottery bond proceeds will create jobs,
10 further economic development, finance public education or restore and protect parks,
11 beaches, watersheds and native fish and wildlife, and is authorized based on the finding that
12 wastewater infrastructure is an integral part of the commercial and industrial infrastructure
13 of this state, and improving wastewater infrastructure will promote economic development
14 and watershed health.
15 SECTION 38. Section 12, chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025, is amended to read:
16 Sec. 12. (1) A public university that is carrying out a qualified project shall require each con-
17 tractor in a contract with an estimated cost of $200,000 or greater to:
18 (a) Employ apprentices to perform 15 percent of the work hours that workers in apprenticeable
19 occupations perform under the contract, in a manner consistent with the apprentices’ respective
20 apprenticeship training programs;
21 (b) Establish and execute a plan for outreach, recruitment and retention of women, minority
22 individuals and veterans to perform work under the contract, with the aspirational target of having
23 at least 15 percent of total work hours performed by individuals in one or more of those groups;
24 (c) Provide health insurance and retirement benefits to workers employed by the contractor; and
25 (d) Require any subcontractor engaged by the contractor to abide by the requirements set forth
26 in paragraphs (a), (b) and (c) of this subsection, if the work to be performed under the subcontract
27 has an estimated cost of $200,000 or greater.
28 (2) On or before February 1 of each year, each public university that is carrying out a qualified
29 project shall report to the Joint Committee on Ways and Means or Joint Interim Committee on
30 Ways and Means, as part of the report required under ORS 350.379, on:
31 (a) The amount of work performed on qualified projects by apprentices;
32 (b) The amount of work performed on qualified projects by women, minority individuals and
33 veterans; and
34 (c) The types and costs of health insurance and retirement benefits provided to workers by
35 contractors and subcontractors.
36 (3) The requirements of this section are in addition to, and not in lieu of, the requirements im-
37 posed under ORS 350.379.
38 (4) As used in this section:
39 (a) “Apprentice” has the meaning given that term in ORS 660.010.
40 (b) “Apprenticeable occupation” has the meaning given that term in ORS 660.010.
41 (c) “Apprenticeship training program” means the total system of apprenticeship that a particular
42 local joint committee, as defined in ORS 660.010, operates, including the local joint committee’s
43 registered standards and all other terms and conditions for qualifying, recruiting, selecting, em-
44 ploying and training apprentices in an apprenticeable occupation.
45 (d) “Minority individual” has the meaning given that term in ORS 200.005.
[24]

A-Eng. SB 5701
1 (e) “Qualified project” means the following capital construction projects:
2 (A) The Portland State University Portland Center for the Performing Arts Academic Building
3 referenced in section 1 (1)(f) [of this 2025 Act], chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025;
4 (B) The University of Oregon Child Behavioral Health Building project referenced in section 1
5 (1)(g) [of this 2025 Act], chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025;
6 (C) The Southern Oregon University Creative Industries/Student Success project referenced in
7 section 1 (1)(h) [of this 2025 Act], chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025; [and]
8 (D) The Western Oregon University Data Center project referenced in section 1 (1)(i) [of this
9 2025 Act], chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025[.]; and
10 (E) The Oregon State University Cascades Student Health and Recreation Center project
11 referenced in section 1 (1)(j), chapter 630, Oregon Laws 2025, as amended by section 1 of this
12 2026 Act.
13 (f) “Veteran” has the meaning given that term in ORS 408.225.
14 (g) “Woman” has the meaning given that term in ORS 200.005.
15 SECTION 39. This 2026 Act being necessary for the immediate preservation of the public
16 peace, health and safety, an emergency is declared to exist, and this 2026 Act takes effect
17 on its passage.
